John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools maintain a record of academic excellence, and it continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which is only reinforced with individual and collective success in sport, arts, music and other community activities.
With over 30,000 students all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to give the best level of service to their students and parents..
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education and higher education, for their chosen career and for their role as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a personalised school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain a topic of popular and desirable choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If he spoke a human being in a language he understands, he understands with his mind.
If they spoke in his own language, he understands with his heart."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's recent exams, we can see that languages are leading the ranking tables with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students studying foreign languages achieved a Higher A grade.
The data, compiled from the 74 schools that are members of SCIS, showed that 72 percent of students achieved a Higher A grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German studyers, 69 percent of French studyers and 63 percent studying Spanish achieved A as well.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now, as a subject option, maintained in the same regard as STEM topics (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that from reasons employers gave for the fact they are sending to fill vacancies, 17 percent were attributed to lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming more and more imperative to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more prospective job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Irrespective of the career chosen, learning another language will have a real advantage in the future as it has the ability to stay such a life.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically puts a multilingual lead in the competition.
According to a YouGov poll of over 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation and, by 15 percent, French is the only language spoken with a two-digit percentage.
That is why investing in language learning is now important for today's children.
Knowing more than one language, particularly those of developing economies, children will have a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK when looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages that they can choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future.
It cannot be denied at present, in a global business environment, that languages remain very important for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should really be seen as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's youth.
The faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
