Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have permission to access what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is "world domination."
"We want to do it now," he said of the new business.
"This is a historic moment."
The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their "personal online data shop" or POD.
This may contain contact lists, lists of what to do, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
This is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify have all available on one browser and all at the same time.
What makes the online data store unique is that it is entirely up to the user who can access what kind of information.
The company calls this "personal autonomization through data."
The idea for Inrupt, according to company CEO John Bruce, is that the company brings appropriate resources, process skills and skills to make Solid available to all.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform brought by IBM, some developers in staff who have a contract to work on the project, and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their decentralized applications through the tools available on Inrupt's website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google about whether they should introduce a complete change where all their business models are turned upside down overnight.
"We are not asking their permission."
In a post on Medium published Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new site built on Solid.'
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he established a World Wide Web Consortium at the Institute of Technology in Massachusetts.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been a voice of influence in the net neutrality debate.
Even while launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the Founder and Director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am immensely optimistic for this next era of the web," added Berners-Lee.
