Germany's new war postponed once again
The newest frigate of the German Navy was to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the frigates of the aging Cold War time, but there will not be until at least next year due to systems with defects and rising cost, local media reported.
The commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz," the lead ship of the new flaming brigade of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit citing a spokesman for the military.
The ship was to join the Navy in 2014, but problematic post-delivery issues stained the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships that ordered the Navy back in 2007 will come as a replacement for the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is understood that they will have a strong cannon, an anti-aircraft and anti-ship missile display as well as some cautious technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic singers.
Other important functions include longer maintenance periods - this should be possible to operate the newest frigates up to two years away from home ports.
However, a continuous delay means that the last technology vessels – which said they allow Germany to project power overseas – will already be old until the time they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The F125 frigate of bad misfortune appeared in the news last year, when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard at Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned a vessel to a shipbuilder after delivering.
Little was known about the reasons for this, but German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware flaws" that made the ship useless if deployed on a combat mission.
The defects in the software were particularly important as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ship would be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors - only half of the workers on the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it appeared that the ship is heavily overweight to reduce its performance and limit the Navy's ability to add future updates.
The "Rheinland-Pfalz" of 7,000 tons is understood to be twice as heavy as ships of a similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the price of the entire project - including crew training - is also becoming a problem.
This is said to have reached a shocking amount of €3.1 billion ($3.6bn) - out of an initial €2.2 billion.
The problems of the newest fraggates become especially important in the light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is declining.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, the head of the German parliament's defence committee, acknowledged that the Navy currently "has a shortage of vessels to withstand deployment."
The official said the problem grew over time, because old ships were commissioned but replacement vessels were not provided.
He complained that none of the brigade-class frigates could join the Navy.
The National Trust is mentioned on the bat's secret life
New research being conducted in land in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape when searching for food.
It is hoped that the findings will show new light on the behavior of unique mammals that fly and help guide future conservation activities.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common pipistrelles and soprano as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton at the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in major localities around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
An expert analysis of the sounds of all recordings will ascertain the frequency of bat calls and which species is doing what.
A map of the habitat and a report will then be produced which will create a detailed picture of a landscape scale of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of pastures and how best to maintain bat groves and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and across the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the past century.
They are under threat from building and development work affecting nesting and habitat loss.
Wind and light turbines can also pose a risk, as poisoned papers can capture insects and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
The bats actually aren't blind.
However, due to their notorious hunting traditions their ears are more useful than their eyes when they come to capture prey.
They use sophisticated ecolocality techniques to indicate insects and obstacles in their path when flying.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, inspections of nests and sometimes rescues.
The organisation even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave ground in Dumfries and Galloway, welcoming eight of the Scholls' ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Threave we have a very good area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many veterans trees and all the good habitat.
But there is much more about the bats that is still unknown, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us understand more about what they need to flourish."
He stresses the importance of checking bats for maintenance in properties as it is possible that unintentional destruction of a single maternity nest could kill up to 400 females and juveniles, possibly destroying an entire local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, fasten or upset them or destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer for the Night Butterflies Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we do not yet know how their populations are going."
