Donald Trump, the President of the United States, gave the first warning earlier this year by taxing major Chinese exporters including solar panels, iron and aluminium.
The most significant increase came this week with new tariffs affecting goods amounting to $200 billion (£150 billion), effectively taxing all goods entering the United States from China.
Beijing retaliated each time in the same way, while more recently it was presenting tariffs of five to ten percent on $60 billion worth of American goods.
China has pledged to agree with the United States every time, and it is unlikely that the world's second largest economy will give up in the near future.
The fact that Washington makes a move back means accepting the demands, but publicly the fact that China surrenders to the United States will be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, China's president.
However, experts say that if Beijing works wisely, the pressures of the U.S. trade war can positively support China in the long run by reducing the interdependence of both economies.
