Syria stands "ready" for refugees to return, says Foreign Minister
Syria says it stands ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is calling for help to rebuild the country destroyed by a war that lasted more than seven years.
Speaking to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions in the country are improving.
"Today the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government is continuing to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normalcy.
All conditions are now present for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that targeted their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that since the war began in 2011 more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country.
Six million more people still living in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would welcome aid in rebuilding the destroyed country.
But he stressed that he would not accept conditional assistance or help from countries that sponsored the sedition.
