Update on Red Tide: Concentrations decline in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The most recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decrease in Red Tide concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, conditions of overgrowth of algae in isolated areas are being reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - suggesting decreased concentrations.
The Red Tide which is an overgrowth of algae extends about 130 miles of the coast from the upper Pinellas to the lower Lee countries.
The isolated areas can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but at fewer sites related to last week.
Red Tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Average near-coastal or offshore concentrations of Pinellas County have been reported in the last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations near the coast or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to average concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations near the coast or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in Northwest Florida during the past week.
